{"id":"cond-mat/0105406","submitter":"Boris N. Narozhny","authors":"Gabor Zala, B.N. Narozhny, and I.L. Aleiner","title":"Interaction corrections at intermediate temperatures: I. Longitudinal\n  conductivity and kinetic equation","comments":"32 pages, 24 figures, some figures in postscript 3","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.64.214204","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat","license":null,"abstract":"  It is well known that electron-electron interaction in disordered systems\nleads to logarithmically divergent Altshuler-Aronov corrections to conductivity\nat low temperatures ($T\\tau\\ll 1$; $\\tau$ is the elastic mean-free time). This\npaper is devoted to the fate of such corrections at intermediate temperatures\n$T\\tau\\ge 1$. We show that in this (ballistic) regime the temperature\ndependence of conductivity is still governed by the same physical processes as\nthe Altshuler-Aronov correction - scattering by Friedel oscillations. However,\nin this regime the correction is linear in temperature; the value and even the\n{\\em sign} of the slope depends on the strength of electron-electron\ninteraction. We show that the slope is directly related to the renormalization\nof the spin susceptibility and grows as the system approaches the ferromagnetic\nStoner instability. Also, we obtain the temperature dependence of the\nconductivity in the cross-over region between the diffusive and the ballistic\nregimes. Finally, we derive the quantum kinetic equation, which describes\nelectron transport for arbitrary value of $T\\tau$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 21 May 2001 22:21:06 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 14 Sep 2001 15:49:43 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-07"}
